  "description": "A graph is a mathematical structure consisting of objects (called vertices or nodes) and connections between them (called edges). Draw a dot for each vertex and a line for each edge, and you have a picture of a graph. Graphs formalize any situation where things are related to other things: cities connected by roads, people who know each other, web pages linked by hyperlinks, atoms bonded in a molecule.\nFormally, a graph G=(V,E)G = (V, E) consists of a set VV of vertices and a set EE of edges. In an undirected graph, each edge is an unordered pair {u,v}\\{u, v\\} — the connection between uu and vv runs both ways. In a directed graph (or digraph), each edge is an ordered pair (u,v)(u, v) — the connection runs from uu to vv but not necessarily back. A graph with no multiple edges between the same pair of vertices and no edges from a vertex to itself is called simple.\n",
  "name": "Graph",
